oai_qdc:qualifieddc.dc:title: Front of Cragfont
oai_qdc:qualifieddc.dc:description: Exterior view of the front of Cragfont. The two-story home is constructed of Tennessee limestone. The home has several large iron stars attached through iron rods, barred cellar windows, windows with shutters, and windows above the door. The wooden cornice, with modillions and billet molding, runs along the facade. An American flag is hanging from the front of the house.

The late Georgian style home was built between 1798 and 1802, and was originally home of General James Winchester. It was named after the Rocky Bluff it is located on. Cragfont was occupied by the Winchester family until 1864.
